Document: Static Typing
Path: godot/tutorials/scripting/gdscript/static_typing.rst
Summary: This section lists global scope methods that are not statically typed and their available statically typed equivalents.

Global scope methods are not statically typed, but they have typed counterparts available. These methods return statically typed values:

- abs():
    - Statically typed equivalents: absf(), absi()
    - Statically typed equivalents: Vector2.abs(), Vector2i.abs()
    - Statically typed equivalents: Vector3.abs(), Vector3.abs()
    - Statically typed equivalents: Vector4.abs(), Vector4i.abs()
- ceil():
    - Statically typed equivalents: ceilf(), ceili()
    - Statically typed equivalents: Vector2.ceil()
    - Statically typed equivalents: Vector3.ceil()
    - Statically typed equivalents: Vector4.ceil()
- clamp():
    - Statically typed equivalents: clampf(), clampi()
    - Statically typed equivalents: Vector2.clamp(), Vector2i.clamp()
    - Statically typed equivalents: Vector3.clamp(), Vector3i.clamp()
    - Statically typed equivalents: Vector4.clamp(), Vector4i.clamp()
    - Statically typed equivalents: Color.clamp() (untyped clamp() does not work on Color)
- floor():
    - Statically typed equivalents: floorf(), floori()
    - Statically typed equivalents: Vector2.floor()
    - Statically typed equivalents: Vector3.floor()
    - Statically typed equivalents: Vector4.floor()
- lerp():
    - Statically typed equivalents: lerpf()
    - Statically typed equivalents: Vector2.lerp()
    - Statically typed equivalents: Vector3.lerp()
    - Statically typed equivalents: Vector4.lerp()
    - Statically typed equivalents: Color.lerp()
    - Statically typed equivalents: Quaternion.slerp()
    - Statically typed equivalents: Basis.slerp()
    - Statically typed equivalents: Transform2D.interpolate_with()
    - Statically typed equivalents: Transform3D.interpolate_with()
- round():
    - Statically typed equivalents: roundf(), roundi()
    - Statically typed equivalents: Vector2.round()
    - Statically typed equivalents: Vector3.round()
    - Statically typed equivalents: Vector4.round()
- sign():
    - Statically typed equivalents: signf()
    - Statically typed equivalents: signi()
    - Statically typed equivalents: Vector2.sign(), Vector2i.sign()
    - Statically typed equivalents: Vector3.sign(), Vector3i.sign()
    - Statically typed equivalents: Vector4.sign(), Vector4i.sign()
- snapped():
    - Statically typed equivalents: snappedf()
    - Statically typed equivalents: snappedi()
    - Statically typed equivalents: Vector2.snapped(), Vector2i.snapped()
    - Statically typed equivalents: Vector3.snapped(), Vector3i.snapped()
    - Statically typed equivalents: Vector4.snapped(), Vector4i.snapped()

When using static typing, use the typed global scope methods whenever possible. This ensures safe lines and benefits from typed instructions for better performance.
---CHUNK---
Document: Static Typing
Path: godot/tutorials/scripting/gdscript/static_typing.rst
Summary: Explains how to handle `UNSAFE_PROPERTY_ACCESS` and `UNSAFE_METHOD_ACCESS` warnings when dealing with dynamically typed objects in GDScript.

`UNSAFE_PROPERTY_ACCESS` and `UNSAFE_METHOD_ACCESS` warnings occur when attempting to set a property or call a method on an object whose declared type does not contain that property or method, even if the underlying object instance does.

For example, if you have an object with a script attached using `class_name MyScript` that `extends Node2D`, and you have a reference to this object as a `Node2D` (e.g., from the physics system), you might try to check for and access properties or methods dynamically:

GDScript:
    if "some_property" in node_2d:
        node_2d.some_property = 20  # Produces UNSAFE_PROPERTY_ACCESS warning.

    if node_2d.has_method("some_function"):
        node_2d.some_function()  # Produces UNSAFE_METHOD_ACCESS warning.

These warnings appear because `some_property` and `some_function` are not defined in the `Node2D` class. To safely perform these operations, you can first check if the object is of type `MyScript` using the `is` keyword, then declare a variable with the `MyScript` type to access its properties and methods:

GDScript:
    if node_2d is MyScript:
        var my_script: MyScript = node_2d
        my_script.some_property = 20
        my_script.some_function()

Alternatively, you can declare a variable and use the `as` operator to attempt a cast. Then, check if the cast was successful by verifying that the variable is not `null`:

GDScript:
    var my_script := node_2d as MyScript
    if my_script != null:
        my_script.some_property = 20
        my_script.some_function()
---CHUNK---
Document: static_typing
Path: godot/tutorials/scripting/gdscript/static_typing.rst
Summary: This chunk discusses handling UNSAFE_CAST warnings when accessing properties dynamically in GDScript.

UNSAFE_CAST warning
In this example, we would like the label connected to an object entering our collision area to show the area's name. Once the object enters the collision area, the physics system sends a signal with a Node2D object, and the most straightforward (but not statically typed) solution to do what we want could be achieved like this:

GDScript:
    func _on_body_entered(body: Node2D) -> void:
        body.label.text = name  # Produces UNSAFE_PROPERTY_ACCESS warning.

This piece of code produces an UNSAFE_PROPERTY_ACCESS warning because label is not defined in Node2D. To solve this, we could first check if the label property exist and cast it to type Label before settings its text property like so:

GDScript:
    func _on_body_entered(body: Node2D) -> void:
        if "label" in body:
            (body.label as Label).text = name  # Produces UNSAFE_CAST warning.

However, this produces an UNSAFE_CAST warning because body.label is of a Variant type. To safely get the property in the type you want, you can use the Object.get() method which returns the object as a Variant value or returns null if the property doesn't exist. You can then determine whether the property contains an object of the right type using the is keyword, and finally declare a statically typed variable with the object:

GDScript:
    func _on_body_entered(body: Node2D) -> void:
        var label_variant: Variant = body.get("label")
        if label_variant is Label:
            var label: Label = label_variant
            label.text = name
---CHUNK---
Document: Static Typing
Path: godot/tutorials/scripting/gdscript/static_typing.rst
Summary: This chunk explains cases where type hints cannot be used in GDScript, leading to syntax errors.

To wrap up this introduction, let's mention cases where you can't use type hints. This will trigger a syntax error.

1. You can't specify the type of individual elements in an array or a dictionary:

GDScript:
        var enemies: Array = [$Goblin: Enemy, $Zombie: Enemy]
        var character: Dictionary = {
            name: String = "Richard",
            money: int = 1000,
            inventory: Inventory = $Inventory,
        }

2. Nested types are not currently supported:

GDScript:
        var teams: Array[Array[Character]] = []
---CHUNK---
Document: Static Typing
Path: godot/tutorials/scripting/gdscript/static_typing.rst
Summary: This section introduces the benefits of static typing in GDScript.

Typed GDScript is a powerful tool. It helps you write more structured code, avoid common errors, and create scalable and reliable systems. Static types improve GDScript performance and more optimizations are planned for the future.